%%%%%%%%%
\section{Introduction}
%%%%%%%%%

In the last decade or so, strings on curved backgrounds have been discussed widely in various contexts. Some recent examples are $AdS$/CFT dualities, string on {\it pp}-wave backgrounds \cite{Berenstein:2002jq,Metsaev:2002re}, and time-dependent orbifolds \cite{Khoury:2001bz,Balasubramanian:2002ry,Liu:2002ft,Liu:2002kb}. However, many discussion is limited to backgrounds with light-cone directions ({\it e.g.}, string on {\it pp}-wave backgrounds and time-dependent orbifolds). Otherwise, the technology is often limited to supergravities ({\it e.g.}, for $AdS$/CFT dualities).

This is due to the lack of the string theory on general backgrounds, especially the no-ghost theorem. As is well-known, string theory generally contains negative norm states (ghosts) from timelike oscillators. However, they do not appear as physical states. This is well-established for string theory in flat spacetime \cite{Brower:1972wj}-\cite{Figueroa-O'Farrill:1989hu}. When the background spacetime is curved, things are not clear though. Standard proofs of the no-ghost theorem requires light-cone directions, {\it i.e.}, $d \geq 2$ if the background is written as $ \IR^{1,d-1} \times K $, where $K$ is a unitary CFT. This is true both in the old covariant quantization (OCQ) and in the BRST quantization (Table~\ref{table:standard_proofs})%
\footnote{There are several attempts of the $d=1$ proof in the old covariant quantization. For some discussion, see our first paper \cite{Asano:2000fp}. We will also discuss them thoroughly in our future paper \cite{3rd}.}. 

%In OCQ, some proofs use the ``DDF operators" to explicitly construct the observable Hilbert space to show the theorem \cite{Brower:1972wj,Schwarz:1972ix,Brower:1973iz}. This proof assumes flat spacetime and cannot be extended to the more general cases. Goddard and Thorn's proof \cite{Goddard:1972iy,Thorn:1987xy} is similar to this traditional one, but is formulated without explicit reference to the DDF operators. Since it only requires the existence of a flat light-cone vector, the proof can be extended easily to $d \geq 2$.

%The BRST quantization work more generally. Many proofs can be easily extended to the general $c=26$ CFT on $ \IR^{d-1,1} \times K $, where $2 \leq d \leq 26$ and $K$ corresponds to a compact unitary CFT of central charge $ c_{K} = 26-d $ \cite{Kato:1983im,Frenkel:1986dg,Spiegelglas:1987xe,Ghoshal:1991dn,Polchinski:rq}. 
%Again these proofs admit the simple extension to $d \geq 2$. 
%Many proofs can be extended easily to the general $c=26$
%CFT with $d$-dimensional Minkowski spacetime $ {\cal M}^{(1,d-1)} $ and a
%compact unitary CFT $K$ of central charge $ c_{K} = 26-d $
%\cite{KO,Frenkel:1986dg,spiegelglas,GM,Big}. 
%However, all known proofs assume $d \geq 2$ again.

However, the source of ghosts is the timelike oscillators and the Fadeev-Popov ghosts. Thus, one would expect that no-ghost theorem is valid even for $d=1$ as long as the timelike direction is intact. In fact, in our previous paper \cite{Asano:2000fp}, we show the no-ghost theorem for $d \geq 1$ bosonic string based on the BRST quantization. We heavily used the previous results by Frenkel, Garland and Zuckerman (FGZ) \cite{Frenkel:1986dg}. The purpose of this paper is to extend the proof for the NSR string. 

The proof by FGZ is different from the others. For example, the standard BRST quantization assumes $d \geq 2$ in order to prove the ``vanishing theorem," {\it i.e.}, the BRST cohomology is trivial except at the zero ghost number. However, FGZ's proof of the vanishing theorem essentially does not require $d \geq 2$. Moreover, the power of the technique is not limited to the $d=1$ case. This scheme is especially interesting because it does not even require that the timelike direction be flat; it admits an extension to more general curved backgrounds. As an example, we will discuss $AdS_3$ case in a separate paper \cite{3rd}.

In the next section, we briefly review the BRST quantization of the NSR string. Further details and our conventions are summarized in App.~\ref{sec:appA} and \ref{sec:appB}. The reader who is familiar to the BRST quantization can directly go to the outline of our proof in Sec.~\ref{sec:outline}. The presentation of the proof below is slightly different from our earlier paper \cite{Asano:2000fp}, but the proof itself is very similar.

%Establishing the no-ghost theorem for $d=1$ is then straightforward by calculating the ``index" and ``signature" of the cohomology groups. 

%Thus, in a sense our result is obvious a priori, from Refs.~\cite{Frenkel:1986dg,Lian:1989cy,Figueroa-O'Farrill:1989hu}. But it does not seem to be known well, so it is worth working out this point explicitly in detail.

%The organization of the present paper is as follows. First, in the next section, we briefly review the BRST quantization of the NSR string. Further details and our conventions are summarized in \app{appA} and \ref{sec:appB}. In \sect{vanishing}, we will see a standard proof of the vanishing theorem and review why the standard no-ghost theorem cannot be extended to $d<2$. Then in \sect{fgz}, we prove the vanishing theorem due to FGZ, following Refs.~\cite{Frenkel:1986dg,Lian:1989cy,Figueroa-O'Farrill:1989hu}. We use this result in \sect{no-ghost} to prove the no-ghost theorem for $d=1$.


