To summarize, the matter part of the Hilbert space ${\cal H}$ reduces to a sum of two Verma modules:
\begin{equation}
%
%{\cal H} = 
{\cal H}_{h^{0},h^{K}} = 
{\cal V}(\hat{c}^0=1, h^{0}<0) \otimes {\cal V}(\hat{c}^{K}=9, h^{K}>0)
% \otimes {\cal F}(b_{-m}, c_{-m}, \bet{-r}, \gam{-r}).
\label{eq:hilbert}
%
\end{equation}
for the NS-sector, and similarly for the R-sector.%
\footnote{See the footnote~\ref{ft:inner_product}.} 
Throughout the discussion of the vanishing theorem in Sec.~\ref{sec:vanishing}, we assume the above form of the Hilbert space. {\it Consequently, the vanishing theorem is valid not only for the $d=1$ case but also for more general backgrounds as long as the matter Hilbert space takes the above form.}
